<h2><i class="mch-book-open"></i> 3.2.1 PROFICIENCY</h2>
<div class="evidenceBorder">
  <h3><i class="mch-search"></i> <img src="../../images/smart-1-1-magnifying-glass.jpg" alt="Image of Magnifying Glass" class="right ppic" />REVIEW. The Competency in Detail</h3>
  <p>The following drop-downs contain information on each of the knowledge areas and skills needed to implement the competency. <strong>Please explore the content below.</strong></p>
  <h3>Ethics</h3>
  <p><strong>Knowledge Areas. </strong>MCH leaders will demonstrate a working knowledge of:</p>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-compass3"></i> <strong>3K1.</strong> Professional ethical/legal principles, values, behaviors.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p><span id="docs-internal-guid-2a50fb03-7fff-5425-35dd-77041c07e5e8">The ethical and legal principles, values, and behaviors  that underlie professional conduct within community, health care, and public health settings</span> are<sup>1,2</sup>:</p>
    <ul>
      <li> <strong>Beneficence:</strong> The obligation to produce benefit for an individual or population. It involves balancing the benefits of an action against the costs.</li>
      <li><strong>Non-maleficence:</strong> The obligation to not cause harm. </li>
      <li><strong>Truthfulness</strong>: The obligation to disclose complete and accurate information to all parties involved in a decision.</li>
      <li><strong>Justice:</strong> A principle that maintains that all individuals have equal worth, and so deserve equal opportunities and treatment.</li>
      <li><strong>Respect for Autonomy:</strong> Respect for individual views must be maintained. However, in MCH, and public health in general, the needs of individuals within the populations must be balanced with the needs of populations. </li>
    </ul>
    </div>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-book"></i> <strong>3K2.</strong> Professional association's code of ethics.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>Many professional associations for those in fields connected to maternal and child health have a code of ethics that clarifies expectations for the conduct and decision-making of professionals within that field. Some examples:  </p>
    <ul>
      <li>American Medical Association: <a href="https://code-medical-ethics.ama-assn.org/">Code of Ethics</a></li>
      <li>American Public Health Association: <a href="https://www.apha.org/membership/code-of-conduct">Code of Conduct</a></li>
      <li>National Association of Social Workers (NASW): <a href="https://www.socialworkers.org/About/Ethics/Code-of-Ethics/Code-of-Ethics-English">Code of Ethics</a></li>
      <li>American Public Health Association (APHA): <a href="https://apha.org/membership/code-of-conduct">Code of Ethics</a></li>
      <li>National Association for the Education of Young Children (NAEYC): <a href="https://www.naeyc.org/files/naeyc/file/positions/PSETH05.pdf">Code of Ethics</a></li>
    </ul>
    </div>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-list-ordered"></i> <strong>3K3. </strong>IRB processes and criteria.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>In his <em>Formula for Humanity</em>, Immanuel Kant stated the categorical imperative that people should never be treated as a means to an end.<sup>3</sup> Though he formulated this idea long before human subjects research came to be, it has come to be a foundational principle of research ethics. </p>
    <p>In the 20th century, the need became obvious for formal efforts to guide ethical research on human subjects. The Nuremberg Code established a set of international ethical guidelines for conducting research with humans in response to the atrocities committed by Nazi doctors during World War II. Some years later, reports of unethical research in the United States prompted Congress to convene an advisory committee that produced the <a href="https://www.hhs.gov/ohrp/regulations-and-policy/belmont-report/index.html">Belmont Report</a>. That report, published in 1979, outlined appropriate research behavior regarding human subjects. It was the basis for subsequent legislation specifying protections for people participating in research. In 1991, Congress approved the Federal Policy for the Protection of Human Subjects, also called the <a href="https://www.hhs.gov/ohrp/regulations-and-policy/regulations/common-rule/index.html">Common Rule</a>, which was adopted by 16 federal departments and agencies. The Common Rule was revised in 2017.</p>
    <p>A key protection prescribed by the Common Rule is the appropriate review and approval of research by an <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=U8fme1boEbE&feature=youtu.be">Institutional Review Board</a> (IRB). An IRB is composed of at least five members of varying backgrounds and institutional affiliations. The IRB reviews potential research to ensure that ethical guidelines and regulatory requirements are met, and that potential participants understand the study and its potential risks and can choose whether or not to participate. This latter process is known as <a href="https://www.hhs.gov/ohrp/regulations-and-policy/guidance/faq/informed-consent/index.html">informed consent</a>.</p>
    <p><strong>Informed consent</strong> is one of seven main principles that have been described as guiding the conduct of ethical research. The remainder are:<sup>4</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li> <strong>Social and clinical value</strong>: A research study should address a question with an answer that has value to society or for present or future patients with a particular condition.</li>
      <li><strong>Scientific validity</strong>: The study should be designed so that it will get an understandable answer to the research question. It should
        <ul>
          <li>Address a research question that is answerable</li>
          <li>Use valid and feasible research methods </li>
          <li>Have a clear scientific objective</li>
          <li>Use accepted principles, methods, and reliable practices</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
      <li><strong>Fair subject selection</strong>: Who should participate in the study? The study&rsquo;s scientific goals should be the primary basis for who should be recruited and enrolled as a human subject.</li>
      <li><strong>Favorable risk-benefit ratio</strong>: Study design should minimize the risks and inconvenience to research subjects and maximize the potential benefits. The potential benefits should be equal to or greater than the risks.</li>
      <li><strong>Independent review</strong>: The study should be evaluated by an IRB, granting agency, or other monitoring group to determine whether it fulfills the following requirements:
        <ul>
          <li>Those conducting the trial are sufficiently free of bias</li>
          <li>The study sufficiently protects research subjects</li>
          <li>The trial has been ethically designed </li>
          <li>The risk–benefit ratio is favorable</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
      <li><strong>Respect for potential and enrolled subjects</strong>: The recruitment and enrollment process should be respectful of individuals, whether or not they choose to participate in the study. This includes:
        <ul>
          <li>Respecting privacy and confidentiality</li>
          <li>Allowing research subjects to change their mind and withdraw from the study without penalty</li>
          <li>Providing new information about the study that changes the risk-benefit ratio</li>
          <li>Monitoring subjects and providing treatment for, and/or withdrawing, those who suffer adverse side-effects or negative changes in health status </li>
          <li>Providing research volunteers with the study results</li>
          </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </div>
	<button class="accordion"><i class="mch-book"></i> <strong>3K4.</strong> IRBs ensure ethical study designs.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>Involving individuals with practical experience (people directly affected by the research topic) throughout the research process can significantly strengthen the ethical design of studies in maternal and child health. Here's how: </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Enhanced risk-benefit analysis: Studies often underestimate the potential burdens participants may face. Practical experience can highlight concerns researchers might miss, allowing IRBs to ensure the research offers a clear benefit that outweighs potential risks.<sup>5</sup></li>
      <li>Community perspectives in research: Research designs can be insensitive to nuances that impact participant understanding and comfort. Practical experience can inform recruitment strategies, consent forms, and interview methods, promoting  understanding and fostering trust with participants.<sup>6</sup></li>
    </ul>
    </div>
 
  
 
  <p><strong>Skills</strong></p>
  <p><strong><em>Foundational. </em></strong><em>At a foundational level, MCH leaders will be able to:</em></p>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-graph"></i> <strong>3S1.</strong> Understand individual values to deliver ethical policy</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>Understanding individual and community  values is fundamental to delivering ethical and effective care in MCH. Here’s why:</p>
	  <ul>
	  <li>Improved health outcomes: Community beliefs and practices significantly impact health behaviors. For instance, some communities prioritize traditional birthing practices.   If interventions do not take this into account, it can lead to distrust and non-adherence to programs, hindering positive health outcomes<sup>7</sup></li>
	  <li>Reduced health variations: Community competency allows MCH professionals to identify and address existing variations. Research shows that African American and Latina mothers are less likely to receive prenatal care or utilize preventive services when they feel  misunderstood by health care providers.<sup>8</sup></li>
	  <li>Community trust: Responsive practices acknowledge and respect individual values. This fosters trust, and active participation in MCH programs. Studies demonstrate that tailored interventions for postpartum depression screening have led to increased help-seeking behaviors among  mothers.<sup>9</sup></li></ul>
  </div>
	<button class="accordion"><i class="mch-graph"></i> <strong>3S2.</strong> Identify/address ethical issues in care/human subjects research</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>As a first step, determine whether a situation involves ethics. Consider the following: &ldquo;Does it concern right and wrong, rights and responsibilities, human welfare, or individuals&rsquo; best interests?&rdquo;<sup>10</sup> If the answer to any of those points is yes, the situation involves ethics.</p>
    <p>Next, decide whether the situation is an ethical responsibility or dilemma. An ethical responsibility generally will be spelled out in the professional code of ethics for your field. Guidance on how to act should be clear, though the actions called for in the code of ethics may not please the constituents with whom you are working and also may conflict with your personal code of ethics. If you follow the code of ethics, however, you will be able to cite it as the reason for your decision.</p>
    <p>If it is not an ethical responsibility, a situation is an ethical dilemma. A situation will be one or the other, but not both.</p>
  </div>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-medkit"></i> <strong>3S3.</strong> Identify ethical implications of <span id="docs-internal-guid-98adf9a9-7fff-1b24-e7ca-1bbbc0e76e1e">health variations.</span></button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>The Department of Health and Human Services describes health variations as &ldquo;differences in health outcomes that are closely linked with social, economic, and environmental factors&rdquo;<sup>11</sup> Health variations put certain groups at higher risk of disease and worse health outcomes when compared to other groups. </p>
  </div>
  
  
 
  <p><em><strong>Advanced.</strong> Building on the foundational skills, MCH leaders will be able to:</em></p>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-comment-1"></i> <strong>3S4.</strong> Discuss ethical dilemmas affecting MCH.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>It can be difficult and sometimes uncomfortable to discuss ethical dilemmas and issues with others. Nonetheless, these discussions can be valuable learning experiences for those who participate in them and may even be essential to resolving a challenging situation in the workplace.<sup>13</sup> </p>
    <p>An ethical dilemma involves deliberation between two courses of action that are morally justifiable and appear to be &ldquo;correct.&rdquo; Frequently, choosing one course of action over another will benefit one party and cost the other in some way.</p>
    <p>When facilitating discussions about ethical dilemmas, the following questions may be useful: </p>
    <ul>
      <li>What effect would the decision have on the individuals involved?</li>
      <li>What effect or cost will the decision have for the decision maker?</li>
      <li>What effect might the decision have on the organization involved or the public&rsquo;s perception?</li>
      <li>What values are conflicting?</li>
      <li>What are the possible legal considerations?</li>
      <li>Does the situation involve a combination of ethical dilemma types (both personal cost and values)?</li>
      <li>Will it cost the decision maker his or her job?</li>
      <li>How would the decision maker feel if his or her actions and decisions were on the front page of the local newspaper or on the nightly news?</li>
      <li>What is the cost of inaction?</li>
      <li>What resources are available in the agency/organization to help deal with ethical dilemmas? How does one access these resources?</li>
      <li>Does the agency or organization support ethical behavior? Would one be penalized for bringing unethical behavior to the organization&rsquo;s attention?</li>
      <li>How might rationalization come into play in the scenario?</li>
      <li>How will the public perceive the actions and/or decisions?<sup>14</sup></li>
    </ul>
  </div>
    
